  "response": "Walking around Mars without a spacesuit would be a very, very bad idea. Here's what would happen, in a very short period:\n\n*   **Suffocation:** The Martian atmosphere is only about 1% the density of Earth's atmosphere and is composed mostly of carbon dioxide (CO2). You would quickly lose consciousness due to lack of oxygen, probably within 15-20 seconds, and die within minutes. You cannot hold your breath; the CO2 in your lungs would quickly diffuse into your bloodstream.\n\n*   **Explosive Decompression:** The low atmospheric pressure would cause the water in your blood and tissues to boil. This is called ebullism. Your body would swell up considerably, though not explode like in science fiction movies. This is due to the vapor pressure of water at low atmospheric pressures.\n\n*   **Extreme Temperature:** Mars is very cold. The average temperature is around -62 degrees Celsius (-80 degrees Fahrenheit). The thin atmosphere would provide very little insulation, so you would freeze relatively quickly. This would accelerate tissue damage.\n\n*   **Radiation Exposure:** Mars lacks a global magnetic field and has a very thin atmosphere, so you would be exposed to high levels of cosmic and solar radiation. While this wouldn't be the first thing to kill you, it would cause severe DNA damage and increase your risk of cancer later on.\n\nIn summary, you would quickly suffocate, experience ebullism, freeze, and be exposed to dangerous radiation, leading to death in a matter of minutes. A spacesuit is absolutely essential for survival on Mars.",
